iliopsoas muscle is a key hip flexor composed of the psoas major and iliacus muscles. It plays a crucial role in activities involving hip flexion, such as climbing stairs or rising from a seated position. The muscle attaches to the \u003Cstrong\u003Elesser trochanter of the femur\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the correct answer in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater trochanter of the femur\u003C/strong\u003E serves as an attachment site for other muscles, such as the gluteus medius and minimus, but not the iliopsoas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior superior iliac spine\u003C/strong\u003E is the attachment site for the sartorius muscle and the inguinal ligament, not the iliopsoas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eischial tuberosity\u003C/strong\u003E is the attachment site for the hamstring muscles, not the iliopsoas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epubic symphysis\u003C/strong\u003E is a cartilaginous joint between the left and right pubic bones and is not related to the attachment of the iliopsoas muscle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The iliopsoas muscle is a major hip flexor composed of the psoas major and iliacus muscles.","The iliopsoas muscle attaches to the lesser trochanter of the femur.","Understanding muscle attachments is crucial for diagnosing musculoskeletal injuries and planning surgical interventions."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences.","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63811"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18242"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63811"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T20:37:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T20:38:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10956"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78449"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"gro